(v) You know, if you decided to reject the null hypothesis, the probability that you are 
making the wrong decision. 
(vi) You have a reliable experimental fi nding in the sense that if, hypothetically, the experi- 
ment were repeated a great number of times, you would obtain a signif i cant result on 
99% of occasions. (Oakes, 1986, p.&nbsp;79). 
The results are displayed in Table&nbsp;1.1. The mean number of true responses was 
2.5; only three psychologists correctly marked all six statements as false, and one of 
