bility before the seventeenth century.</li><li>Introduces the calculus of expectation, the concept of statistics, and the art of conjecturing.</li></ul><p>Chapter 4: The Classical Theory of Statistical Inference</p><ul><li>Discusses Bayes' theorem and its implications, followed by Laplace's contributions.</li><li>Presents criticisms of the classical theory.</li></ul><p>Chapter 5: Nineteenth-Century Developments in Statistics</p><ul><li>Provides an overview of descriptive statistics, precursors of significance testing, and the application of the normal distribution to populations.</li></ul><p>Chapter 6: The Frequency Theory of Probability</p><ul><li>Explores the Principle of Indifference, the main proponents of the frequency theory, and the concept of randomness.</li></ul><p>Chapter 7: The Fisher and Neyman-Pearson Theories of Statistical Inference</p><ul><li>Discusses Fisher's maximum likelihood, significance testing, and fiducial probability, along with Neyman and Pearson's hypothesis testing and confidence intervals.</li></ul><p>Chapter 8: Bayesian Theories of Probability and Statistical Inference</p><ul><li>Discusses logical theories of probability as proposed by Keynes, Jeffreys, and Jaynes, as well as personalist theories of probability.</li></ul><p>These chapters provide a thorough overview of the foundations of probability and statistical inference, tracing their development through history and examining their philosophical underpinnings.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-gro